					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I'm a newbie myself but yeah maybe you shouldn't bother too much with buffers and stuff that early. Just get Pong working first then try adding buffers.<br /><br />But that's one of the things I don't like about the Nerdy Nights guide (although it's an excellent guide for other reasons), he puts all the logic in the NMI. I had a simple delay routine made out of nested loops which delays for about half a second that's supposed to happen everytime you score in Pong. But half a second is too long for the NMI, so the delay never happened. When I moved it to the main loop (that's called &quot;Forever&quot; in the Nerdy Nights) everything worked. I didn't bother with buffers though.<br /><br />If you are doing the logic-in-main approach, just make sure you have all the graphic updating code in the NMI and the controller reading (and other logic if any) in the main loop.<br /><br />And whenever you change something, make sure you change as few things as possible between testing. If you change too much it's impossible to know what change it is that breaks your program.</div>

