					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Pokun wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I had a simple delay routine made out of nested loops which delays for about half a second</div><br />That's not how delays should be implemented, regardless of whether this loop is inside the NMI handler or not.<br /><br />The thing is you shouldn't stop everything to concentrate on a single task. A game is a collection of smaller systems that run in parallel, like the game engine, the music engine, and so on. If you have one of these subsystems hog the CPU with a task that's supposed span several frames, all other subsystems will stop, and that will cause important things like timers, music or raster effects to completely stop working during this time.<br /><br />Games must do everything step by step. Every frame, each subsystem gets a chance to update itself, and they should only advance the equivalent of one frame before releasing the CPU for the other subsystems that also need updating every frame. A subsystem can choose not to update itself, but it should never interfere with the other ones.<br /><br />The correct way to implement delays is to use counters, and perform certain tasks (the ones you want to delay) only when the counter is 0. For example:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">IF COUNTER IS 0:<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;UPDATE GAME OBJECTS;<br />ELSE<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;DECREMENT COUNTER;<br />END IF</div><br />This will pause only the updating of game objects, until the counter reaches 0. So, if you want to pause the objects for 2 seconds, just set the counter to 120. But everything else that needs to run will keep running, you won't be pausing your whole program just so that objects won't move.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">But half a second is too long for the NMI, so the delay never happened. When I moved it to the main loop (that's called &quot;Forever&quot; in the Nerdy Nights) everything worked.</div><br />That's probably because new NMIs were interrupting the wait loop of the previous NMI, and the game logic was running anyway. Moving the wait loop to the main loop might have given you the result you wanted, but like I said above it's a very bad way to implement several-frame delays.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

