				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">Pokun wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I had a simple delay routine made out of nested loops which delays for about half a second</div><br />That's not how delays should be implemented, regardless of whether this loop is inside the NMI handler or not.<br /><br />The thing is you shouldn't stop everything to concentrate on a single task. A game is a collection of smaller systems that run in parallel, like the game engine, the music engine, and so on. If you have one of these subsystems hog the CPU with a task that's supposed span several frames, all other subsystems will stop, and that will cause important things like timers, music or raster effects to completely stop working during this time.<br /><br />Games must do everything step by step. Every frame, each subsystem gets a chance to update itself, and they should only advance the equivalent of one frame before releasing the CPU for the other subsystems that also need updating every frame. A subsystem can choose not to update itself, but it should never interfere with the other ones.<br /><br />The correct way to implement delays is to use counters, and perform certain tasks (the ones you want to delay) only when the counter is 0. For example:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">IF COUNTER IS 0:<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;UPDATE GAME OBJECTS;<br />ELSE<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;DECREMENT COUNTER;<br />END IF</div><br />This will pause only the updating of game objects, until the counter reaches 0. So, if you want to pause the objects for 2 seconds, just set the counter to 120. But everything else that needs to run will keep running, you won't be pausing your whole program just so that objects won't move.<br /></div><br />Oh thank you for that. My simple delay routine works ok for Pong but if I would add music or something to it, it would stop everytime my delay is executed.<br /><br />My point was that if you have logic code in the NMI and that code is too long for the NMI, it will never finish before the next NMI starts as Tokumaru said. But for a game with simple logic like this it probably won't matter if you put it in NMI or in the main loop.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">chowder wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">this forum seems targeted to more advanced topics, and people who actually know what they're doing <img src="./images/smilies/icon_razz.gif" alt=":P" title="Razz" /><br /></div><br />Yeah but you can learn tons of stuff by just browsing around this forum or by searching for things you are wondering about.</div>

